# Reagents

Categories: nucleoside phosphoramidites (the monomers), protecting‑group reagents (temporary masks), activators (to turn the phosphoramidite into a reactive electrophile), oxidation or sulfurization agents (to lock the backbone), capping reagents (to terminate failures), de‑tritylation acids (to expose the next 5′‑OH), drying agents and inert gases (to keep water out), and solid‑support functionalization chemicals (to tether the first nucleoside).

## Precursors

Earliest precursors:

* sulfur dioxide and chlorine (for thionyl chloride and chlorination reactions)
* benzene (for methoxybenzene, benzoic acid)
* propylene (for isopropanol via direct hydriation, isobutyric acid via hydroformylation or oxidation, and acetic acid)
* carbon monoxide or syngas (CO/H2) (for acetic acid (methanol carbonylation), propylene (Fischer-Tropsch), various aldehydes via hydroformylation)
* phosphorous (elemental) for synthesis of Pcl3 (P + Cl2)
* iodine (purchased or obtained from potassium iodide + oxidant)
* chlorine gas. Required for: TCA, DCA, thionyl chloride synthesis (S + Cl2 + SO2 or related routes), PCl3 (P + Cl2). Enables multiple halogenation pathways.

Early precursors:

* thionyl chloride
* acetic acid
* methoxybenzene
* sodium azide
* propylene
* isopropanol
* benzoic acid
* isobutyric acid

