## Miscellaneous reagents

- **Ammonium hydroxide (NH₄OH, concentrated)** – base for de‑protection and cleavage of the solid support.
- **Ammonia (NH₃, aqueous or gaseous)** – used in final de‑protection steps and for cleaning the instrument.
- **Sodium hydroxide, hydrochloric acid, methanol, isopropanol, acetone** – cleaning and slide‑preparation reagents for POSAM and general glassware.
- **Silane coupling agents (epoxysilane, Rain‑X silane)** – surface‑functionalization chemistries for on‑chip synthesis.
- **Water (deionized, for quenching and work‑up)** – used throughout the protocols.

## Nucleoside phosphoramidite monomers

These monomers are the activated P(III) reagents that couple to the free 5′‑hydroxyl of the growing chain, delivering the nucleobase and the protecting‑group suite needed for step‑wise synthesis.

- **dA‑phosphoramidite (dA‑Bz, β‑cyanoethyl, 5′‑DMT)** – provides the adenine unit; the β‑cyanoethyl phosphate mask protects the non‑bridging oxygen during the cycle, the DMT group is the temporary 5′‑protecting group that is removed each round.
- **dG‑phosphoramidite (dG‑ibu, β‑cyanoethyl, 5′‑DMT)** – supplies the guanine unit; isobutyryl protects the exocyclic amine, β‑cyanoethyl protects the phosphate, DMT is the acid‑labile 5′‑OH mask.
- **dC‑phosphoramidite (dC‑Bz, β‑cyanoethyl, 5′‑DMT)** – provides cytosine; benzoyl protects the exocyclic amine, other groups as above.
- **dT‑phosphoramidite (dT, β‑cyanoethyl, 5′‑DMT)** – supplies thymine; no exocyclic‑amine protecting group is needed, β‑cyanoethyl and DMT are the same as for the other bases.
- **Modified phosphoramidites (e.g., dI, LNA‑phosphoramidites, 2′‑O‑TBDMS, 2′‑O‑ACE, 2′‑O‑TOM, etc.)** – used when a non‑canonical base or a ribose‑modification is required; they carry the same protecting‑group pattern (β‑CE, DMT) plus the specific sugar‑ or base‑modification.

## Protecting‑group reagents

These reagents temporarily block reactive hydroxyl, amine or phosphate functions.

- **4,4′‑Dimethoxytrityl chloride (DMT‑Cl)** – installs the acid‑labile 5′‑O‑trityl protecting group on all phosphoramidites.
- **Benzoyl chloride (Bz‑Cl)** – installs the standard benzoyl protection on the exocyclic amines of A and C.
- **Isobutyryl chloride (iBu‑Cl)** – installs the isobutyryl protection on the exocyclic amine of G.
- **Acetyl chloride (Ac‑Cl)** – alternative, milder protection for C (and sometimes A).
- **Phenoxyacetyl chloride (PAC‑Cl), 4‑isopropyl‑phenoxyacetyl chloride (iPr‑PAC‑Cl), dimethylformamidino chloride (dmf‑Cl)** – “mild” amine‑protecting groups used in special applications.
- **β‑Cyanoethyl (CE) group** – attached to the phosphate oxygen of each phosphoramidite; removed in the final ammonia deprotection step by β‑elimination.
- **2‑Cyanoethyl protecting group (same as above)** – same function; often simply called “CE”.
- **2‑(Trimethylsilyl)ethanesulfonyl (SES) group** – an orthogonal, fluoride‑labile phosphate protecting group used in niche phosphoramidite syntheses.
- **2‑Chlorophenyl, 2,5‑dichlorophenyl, 2‑chloro‑4‑nitrophenyl etc. (aryl groups for phosphotriesters)** – mask the non‑bridging oxygen in classic phosphotriester chemistry; removed post‑synthetically by nucleophilic oximolysis.

## Activators or coupling catalysts

These small‑molecule acids/nucleophiles transiently protonate and displace the diisopropylamine of the phosphoramidite, creating a highly electrophilic phosphite that reacts rapidly with the 5′‑OH of the supported strand.

- **1H‑Tetrazole** – classic acidic azole that protonates the phosphoramidite nitrogen and generates a tetrazolyl‑phosphite intermediate.
- **5‑Ethylthio‑1H‑tetrazole (ETT)** – a more acidic tetrazole that gives faster coupling, especially for sterically hindered monomers.
- **5‑Benzylthio‑1H‑tetrazole (BTT)** – similar to ETT, with improved solubility.
- **4,5‑Dicyanoimidazole (DCI)** – a nucleophilic, weak‑acid activator used when tetrazoles are insufficient.
- **2‑Bromo‑4,5‑dicyanoimidazole** – a highly electrophilic activator for difficult couplings.
- **2‑Nitrophenyl‑tetrazoles (o‑ and p‑nitro‑substituted)** – very strong acids that can be used as salts with bases (e.g., DMAP) to increase activation.
- **Benzimidazole‑TFA, benzimidazole‑BF₄, benzimidazole‑HPF₆, benzimidazole‑triflic acid (TfOH)** – salts of strong Brønsted acids that act as “strong‑acid / good‑nucleophile” pairs.
- **Imidazolium‑triflate, N‑methylimidazolium‑triflate, N‑methyl‑benzoimidazolium‑triflate, N‑phenyl‑imidazolium‑triflate** – ionic liquids that serve as both acid and nucleophile in the activation step.
- **4‑Dimethylaminopyridine (DMAP) salts (e.g., DMAP–TfO⁻)** – act as nucleophilic bases in some activator systems.
- **Pyridinium‑trifluoroacetate** – another acidic/nucleophilic pair employed for specialized phosphoramidite couplings.

## Oxidizing reagents

After each coupling, the newly formed phosphite triester is oxidized to the stable phosphate triester, preventing hydrolytic degradation of the growing chain.

- **Iodine (I₂) / water / pyridine / THF (standard “I₂ oxidation”)** – the work‑horse oxidant that gives the native phosphodiester linkage.
- **tert‑Butyl hydroperoxide (t‑BuOOH)** – an anhydrous oxidant used when iodine is undesirable (e.g., for sensitive protecting groups).
- **(1S)-(+)-(10‑Camphorsulfonyl)‑oxaziridine (CSO)** – a mild, non‑acidic oxidant sometimes employed for RNA or base‑sensitive syntheses.

## Sulfurizing reagents

These reagents replace the non‑bridging oxygen of the phosphate with sulfur, generating nuclease‑resistant phosphorothioate linkages.

- **Elemental sulfur (S₈)** – the simplest sulfur donor; reacts with the phosphite to give a P(III)‑S intermediate that is subsequently oxidized to the phosphorothioate.
- **3H‑1,2‑Benzodithiol‑3‑one (Beaucage reagent)** – a fast, soluble sulfur‑transfer reagent giving quantitative thio‑oxidation.
- **Tetraethylthiuram disulfide (TETD)** – an alternative sulfur donor with good solubility in acetonitrile.
- **Phenylacetyl disulfide (PADS)** – a third common sulfurizing reagent used in automated syntheses.

## Capping or acetylating reagents

The capping mixture “caps” failure sequences with an acetyl group, allowing them to be distinguished from full‑length product during purification. Acetylating reagents terminate unreacted 5' -OH chains.

- **Acetic anhydride** – acetylates any free 5′‑OH that failed to couple, preventing further elongation of that strand.
- **1‑Methylimidazole (N‑MeIm)** – a nucleophilic catalyst that accelerates acyl transfer during the capping step.
- **4‑Dimethylaminopyridine (DMAP)** – an alternative, more nucleophilic acylation catalyst sometimes used in capping.

## Acid deprotection reagents

These acids selectively remove the DMT group, exposing the 5′‑hydroxyl for the next coupling while leaving other protecting groups intact.

- **Trichloroacetic acid (TCA, 2–3 % in DCM)** – mild acid used to cleave the 5′‑DMT protecting group, releasing an orange trityl cation that can be monitored spectrophotometrically.
- **Dichloroacetic acid (DCA, 2.5 % in DCM)** – an alternative de‑tritylation acid with similar strength.

## Solvents

All reagents are delivered and washed in rigorously dry, aprotic organic solvents to prevent premature hydrolysis of the moisture‑sensitive phosphoramidites and intermediates.

- **Acetonitrile (anhydrous, “MeCN”)** – the universal solvent for phosphoramidite solutions, activator solutions, and most wash steps.
- **Dichloromethane (DCM, anhydrous)** – used for DMT deprotection and for many washing steps.
- **Tetrahydrofuran (THF, anhydrous)** – co‑solvent for oxidation (I₂/THF) and some alternative oxidations.
- **Toluene** – sometimes employed as a non‑polar wash or for solvent‑exchange steps.
- **Methanol, ethanol, isopropanol, acetone, pentane/hexanes** – used for precipitation, cleaning, and final product isolation.
- **Water (anhydrous for I₂ oxidation; deionized for work‑up)** – required in the iodine oxidation mixture and for quenching reactions.


## Solid‑support / surface‑functionalization reagents

These reagents provide a chemically inert platform that holds the nascent oligonucleotide during the repetitive coupling/oxidation cycles.

- **Controlled‑pore glass (CPG) or silica gel (high‑purity, 500–2000 Å pores)** – the inert solid support to which the 3′‑hydroxyl of the initial nucleoside is covalently attached.
- **Succinic anhydride** – introduces a carboxylic‑acid linker on the support for subsequent amide coupling of the first nucleoside.
- **Epoxysilane, Rain‑X silane solution (chlorotrimethylsilane‑based), other silanes** – used to functionalize glass slides before on‑surface synthesis (POSAM).
- **Sodium hydroxide, hydrochloric acid, methanol, isopropanol, acetone** – cleaning and activation reagents for slide preparation.

## Drying agents, gases, and ancillary chemicals

Maintain anhydrous, inert conditions. Moisture is the principal enemy of P(III) chemistry; these reagents and gases keep the system water‑free.

- **Calcium hydride (CaH₂)** – dries solvents before distillation.
- **Molecular sieves (4 Å, activated)** – keep stored solvents dry.
- **Drierite (anhydrous CaSO₄, indicator)** – monitors and removes residual moisture in gas lines and syringes.
- **Argon or nitrogen gas (dry, inert)** – blankets reaction vessels and supplies the inert atmosphere required for phosphoramidite handling.

## Alternative backbone‑chemistry precursors (non‑phosphoramidite routes)

These reagents belong to historic or alternative synthetic routes (phosphodiester, phosphotriester, H‑phosphonate, methyl‑phosphonate) that preceded or complement modern phosphoramidite chemistry.

- **Methyl phosphorodichloridite (CH₃OPCl₂)** – the P(III) chlorophosphite used to make methyl‑phosphonate or phosphonate backbones.
- **Methyl phosphonamidite (Me‑P‑amidite)** – the phosphonamidite analogue for methyl‑phosphonate synthesis.
- **p‑Toluenesulfonyl chloride (TsCl), mesitylenesulfonyl chloride (MSCl), mesitylenesulfonyl‑nitrotriazole (MSNT)** – “super‑condensing agents” for phosphotriester (P(V)) couplings.
- **2‑Cyanoethyl (CE) group (as a protective group in phosphotriester chemistry)** – also appears in the classic phosphotriester method.
- **2‑Chloro‑phenyl, 2,5‑dichloro‑phenyl aryl phosphate protecting groups** – used for fully protected pentavalent phosphorus in early phosphotriester syntheses.
- **DCC (N,N′‑dicyclohexylcarbodiimide)** – carbodiimide coupling reagent for the original phosphodiester (Khorana) method.
- **pivaloyl chloride, adamantoyl chloride** – acyl‑chloride activators for H‑phosphonate coupling.

## ABI 391‑specific reagents

- **A, G, C, T phosphoramidite bottles (as described in #1)** – the standard monomers used by the instrument.
- **Bottle 9 – tetrazole/acetonitrile (activator solution)** – supplies the coupling activator to the synthesis column.
- **Bottle 11 – acetic anhydride/1‑methylimidazole/THF (capping solution)** – performs the capping step on any unreacted 5′‑OH.
- **Bottle 12 – 1‑methylimidazole (catalyst for capping)** – added to the acetic‑anhydride mixture.
- **Bottle 14 – trichloroacetic acid (de‑tritylation solution)** – removes the DMT group each cycle.
- **Bottle 15 – I₂/H₂O/pyridine/THF (oxidation solution)** – oxidizes the phosphite intermediate to phosphate.
- **Bottle 18 – bulk anhydrous acetonitrile (solvent for all liquid reagents)** – the carrier solvent for monomers, activators, and washes.
- **Concentrated ammonium hydroxide (NH₄OH)** – final cleavage/de‑Cyanoethylation reagent to release the oligo from the solid support.

